\chapter{Jespersen's Cycle (20 pages)}
\label{jespersens-cycle}

\setlength{\epigraphwidth}{.9\textwidth}
\epigraph{The history of negative expressions in various languages makes us witness the following curious fluctuation: the original negative adverb is first weakened, then found insufficient and therefore strengthened, generally through some additional word, and this in its turn may be felt as the negative proper and may then in course of time be subject to the same developments as the original word. \citep[4]{jespersen:1917}}

Originally coined by \cite{dahl:1979}, the term \emph{Jespersen's Cycle} refers to the observation cited above regarding the expression of sentential negation over time for several European languages.\footnote{Sentential negation refers to the semantic property of negating an entire proposition, not just some subpart. It can be distinguished from morphological (e.g. \emph{un-}, \emph{non-}) and constituent negation (e.g. \emph{John might have not understood}) using several diagnostics such as tag questions \citep{klima1964}  and performative paraphrases \cite{payne1985}. Sentential negation is also distinct from but related to the syntactic notion of standard negation \citep{miestamo2005}, which are constructions that can reverse the truth value of a proposition.} In particular, Jespersen noted a pattern in both \emph{formal} and \emph{functional} aspects of negation over time. These two aspects of change can be conceived of as two cycles. Each cycle consists of three stages, connected by two transitions. The first and the last stage of both cycles are equivalent along some dimension, making the net effect of the two transitions cyclic.

The formal cycle consists of two transitions. First, a single negative element is supplemented by additional material. Second, the original negative element is subsequently lost, leaving the added material as the only expression of negation. In the history of both English and French a pre-verbal negative element is supplemented by a post-verbal element, and the pre-verbal element is subsequently lost.  It should be emphasized that the transition from pre- to post-verbal negation is not the only path through the formal cycle. In the most general sense, the formal cycle is the addition and then loss of material. It is a contingent fact, arising from the syntax of  English and French and the source of new formal material, that gives rise to the transition from pre- to post-verbal negation. 

The functional cycle also consists of two transitions. First, a single form of negation is supplemented by an additional form that expresses negation more strongly. Second, this new form weakens and comes to have the same strength as the original negative form. The stronger form of negation is often formed through the addition of another element to the original negative form. The combined elements are weakened over time and come to have the same force as the original negative element by itself. In the history of English and French a pre-verbal element is supplemented by a post-verbal element, which strengthens negation. The meaning of the combined pre- and post-verbal elements weakens over time, and the two elements come to have the same force as the original pre-verbal element in isolation.

In the rest of this chapter we discuss in greater detail the two kinds of cycles stemming from Jespersen's observation. While Jespersen conceptualized the change he observed as a matter of both formal and functional weakening and strengthening, much subsequent work has emphasized only one dimension or the other. Ths is certainly understandable, given that the effect of one cycle has implications for the other. For example, the addition of material often comes with a more restricted and hence stronger meaning. Here we address both cycles individually and the relation between them. 

First, we outline the formal aspects of how negation is expressed. We provide a historical description of the structural forms that express negation at different points in the history of English. We present two syntactic analyses of the structures that characterize the stages of the formal cycle. Second, we outline the function of those forms, describing the meaning of the different forms of negation at different points in time and their semantic and pragmatic content. Finally, we discuss how these two aspects of the cycle relate to change over time. In particular, we note the causal mechanics of each cycle and the conditions for change under both.

Before moving on, we should note that recent work has established the cross-linguistic prevalence of formal cycles in various language families beyond Indo-European, including Uralic, Na-Dene, and Afro-Asiatic languages \textit{inter alia} \citep{vanGelderen2008negative,willis-etal2013}. The variety of patterns evidenced in these diverse languages has led some to suggest the broader term \emph{negative cycle} \citep{vanGelderen2008negative}, in lieu of Jespersen's cycle. This suggestion arguably stems from the conflation of the formal cycle with the particular path from pre- to post-verbal negation found in many of the languages Jespersen discussed. In what follows we will focus on the history of negation in English, however, we will distinguish between the formal cycle, which allows for various paths as the term negative cycle suggests, and the functional cycle.

The reasons for focusing on English are twofold. First, we have historical records of sufficient time depth to track the history of negation. In fact, we have chronologically contiguous corpora from Old English (The York-Toronto-Helsinki Parsed Corpus of Old English Prose (YCOE), \citealt{ycoe}) through Middle English (The Penn-Helsinki Parsed Corpus of Middle English (PPCME2), \citealt{ppcme2})  and beyond (The Penn-Helsinki Parsed Corpus of Early Modern English (PPCEME) \citealt{ppceme}). Second, these corpora provide sufficient data to investigate both qualitative and quantitative aspects of change. This holds especially of negation which is one of the most frequent constructions in all languages. 

The analyses presented in subsequent chapters will take advantage of the resources available for English to study aspects of both the formal and functional cycles. This does not preclude further applications to other languages. But, we should keep in mind that the processes underlying one path through the formal cycle might be distinct from others. That is, there might be multiple phenomena that give rise to similar diachronic forms of negation. Further resources will be required to test, refine, and improve our analyses. A promising route towards this end is the use of semi-automated methods for constructing historical corpora, along the lines of the Penn-York Computer-annotated Corpus of a Large amount of English based on the Text Creation Partnership (PYCCLE-TCP), \cite{pyccle}). Such methods will allow for further investigations into the historical development of both the form and function of negation in diverse languages. For now, we start with English.


\section{The Formal Cycle}

We begin by describing the formal stages of Jespersen's Cycle before turning to syntactic analyses of those structures. We see the first stage of the formal cycle in the history of English with the pre-verbal \emph{\textcolor{red}{ne}} in Old English, which expresses sentential negation alone.

\exg. Ic \textcolor{red}{ne} secge\\
      I \textsc{neg} say\\
      (Old English)


This is followed by a stage of embracing or bipartite negation where a post-verbal negative element is added. This is seen in Middle English, where \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne}} is supplemented by \emph{\textcolor{blue}{not}}.


\exg. I \textcolor{blue}{ne} seye \textcolor{blue}{not}\\
      I \textsc{neg} say \textsc{neg}\\
      (Middle English)

There are several sources that these additional elements are drawn from. Most notably, they are drawn from \emph{negative polarity items}, overwhelmingly the set of \emph{minimizers} (e.g. ``not a drop'', ``not a hair'') and \emph{generalizers} (e.g. ``not ever'', ``not at all'', \citealt{horn:1989}). For example, in the case of English, ``not'' comes from Old English ``nawiht'' (\emph{literally} ``no thing, creature, being''). Other sources include, indefinite pronouns (e.g. ``no one''), negative adverbs (e.g. ``never'') (cf. \citealt{horn:1989,vanGelderen2008negative}), negative verbs (e.g. ``refuse", ``deny", ``reject", ``avoid", ``fail", and ``lack",  \citealt{givon1978}), and the concatenation of negative and existential verbs \citep{croft1991}.

In light of this broad range of sources, it is important to note that the first transition need not consist of the addition of a post-verbal element. For example, in modern African American Vernacular English, negation can be supplemented by a pre-verbal element \emph{eem}, which comes from but is distinct from \emph{even} (cite Jones, 2014):

\ex. You do\textcolor{blue}{n't eem} know.

Given the range of sources for additional negative elements, this is not surprising.  But, again, we should note that the formal cycle is often treated as a transition from pre- to post-verbal negation, there are more paths that the formal cycle can take. This is a contingent fact of word order and negative element source: in the case of English and French, subject-verb-object word order and negative polarity noun phrase objects.

The final stage in the formal cycle is a return to a single negative element. This is seen in Early Modern English, where the preverbal negator in \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne...not}}  is lost, leaving the post-verbal \emph{\textcolor{green}{not}}  as the sole negator.

\exg. I say \textcolor{green}{not}\\
      I say \textsc{neg}\\
      (Early Modern English)

The emergence of  \emph{do}-support in Early Modern English yields a state parallel to Old English with a sole pre-verbal negator:

\exg. I do \textcolor{red}{not} say\\
      I do \textsc{neg} say\\
      (Present-day English)

The contraction of negation offers an even closer parallel to Old English where \emph{ne} contracted with several verbs (e.g. ``ne be'' $\rightarrow$ ``nis'').

% \footnote{The increasing preference of n't over not in colloquial use is illustrated by the use of not contractions of American presidents from Kennedy to Bush. While Kennedy and Nixon still used the uncontracted form not in the majority of cases (during public debates), Bush Sr. and Clinton used this form in only in 14-17\% of all cases (Yaeger-Dror \& Hall-Lew (2002)}

\exg. I do\textcolor{red}{n't} say\\
      I do-\textsc{neg} say\\
      (Present-day English)


