The history of negation in French offers a parallel to the formal cycle in English, although the exact timeline is disputed (cf. \citealt{martineau-mougeon2003}).  The Old French pre-verbal \emph{\textcolor{red}{ne}} becomes Middle French \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne...pas}}, and subsequently Modern Colloquial French post-verbal \emph{\textcolor{green}{pas}}.

\exg. Jeo \textcolor{red}{ne} dis\\
      I \textsc{neg} say\\
      (Old French)

\exg. Je \textcolor{blue}{ne} dis \textcolor{blue}{pas}\\
      I \textsc{neg} say \textsc{neg}\\
      (Middle French)

\exg. Je dis \textcolor{green}{pas}\\
      I say \textsc{neg}\\
      (Modern Colloquial French)

%In the case of French, ``pas'' comes from ``step'', and in fact still has this separate meaning in non-negative contexts.  

