Similar morphological approaches to the formal cycle are adopted by \cite{roberts-roussou2003} and \cite{zeijlstra2004}. The shared aspect of these morphological analyses is the assumption that the underlying syntactic structure remains stable, but the realizations of particular positions within that structure changes. Importantly, since this is the only locus of change, the transitions that constitute the cycle are independent of each other. In fact, the two transitions in the formal cycle are taken to to be independent morphological changes. That is, the fact that both \emph{ne} and \emph{not} show up in the embracing \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne...not}} form is simply the coincidental product of two forms waxing and waning at the same time.

\cite{frisch1997} tests this theoretical prediction using the trajectory of negation in Middle English in the Helsinki corpus of Middle English.\footnote{Portions of this corpus are included in PPCME2 \citep{ppcme2}. For more details see: \url{http://www.ling.upenn.edu/hist-corpora/PPCME2-RELEASE-3/index.html}} First, he notes that if the two transitions are independent of each other, then the co-occurrence of \emph{ne} and \emph{not} in the embracing form should be the product of the probabilities of each occurring. That is, the probability of \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne...not}} is the probability of two independent events \emph{ne} and \emph{not}.

\begin{equation}
	P(ne...not) = P(ne)P(not)
\end{equation}

This works exactly as if we were to flip two independent and fair coins. The probability of both coming up heads would simply be the product of each of the individual coins coming up heads.

\begin{equation}
	P(H,H) = P(H)P(H) = \frac{1}{2}  \times \frac{1}{2}  = \frac{1}{4}
\end{equation}

To obtain these probabilities, Frisch counts the occurrences of \emph{ne} both by itself and as part of \emph{\textcolor{blue}{ne...not}}. Estimating the occurrences of \emph{not} requires a bit more work given that it is often ambiguous between an adverb, a specifier in the negative phrase, or the head of the negative phrase itself. The adverbial instances of \emph{not} can be estimated by noting that other adverbs such as \emph{never} occur pre-verbally around 16\% of the time. Assuming that adverbial \emph{not} is similarly distributed, the number of adverbial instances can be estimated with the appropriate scaling of pre-verbal. The instances where \emph{not} is the head of the negative phrase can be estimated by the occurrence of \emph{not} by itself in interrogatives, which 

